-model" style=3D"text-align:left"><span>Types of Naive Bayes Model</span></=
h2><p dir=3D"ltr"><span>There are three types of Naive Bayes Model :</span>=
</p><h3 id=3D"gaussian-naive-bayes" style=3D"text-align:left"><b><strong>1.=
 Gaussian Naive Bayes </strong></b></h3><p dir=3D"ltr"><span>In </span><a h=
ref=3D"https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/machine-learning/gaussian-naive-bayes/=
" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener"><b><strong>Gaussian Naive Bayes</stron=
g></b></a><span>, continuous values associated with each feature are assume=
d to be distributed according to a Gaussian distribution. A Gaussian distri=
bution is also called </span><a href=3D"https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/maths=
/normal-distribution/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D""><span>Normal distribution=
</span></a><span> When plotted, it gives a bell shaped curve which is symme=
tric about the mean of the feature values as shown below:</span></p><h3 id=
=3D"multinomial-naive-bayes" style=3D"text-align:left"><b><strong>2. Multin=
omial Naive Bayes </strong></b></h3><p dir=3D"ltr"><a href=3D"https://www.g=
eeksforgeeks.org/machine-learning/multinomial-naive-bayes/" target=3D"_blan=
k" rel=3D"noopener"><b><strong>Multinomial Naive Bayes</strong></b></a><spa=
n>is used when features represent the frequency of terms (such as word coun=
ts) in a document. It is commonly applied in text classification, where ter=
m frequencies are important.</span></p><h3 id=3D"bernoulli-naive-bayes" sty=
le=3D"text-align:left"><b><strong>3. Bernoulli Naive Bayes</strong></b></h3=
><p dir=3D"ltr"><a href=3D"https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/machine-learning/b=
ernoulli-naive-bayes/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener"><b><strong>Bernou=
lli Naive Bayes</strong></b></a><span> deals with binary features, where ea=
ch feature indicates whether a word appears or not in a document. It is sui=
ted for scenarios where the presence or absence of terms is more relevant t=
han their frequency. Both models are widely used in document classification=
 tasks</span></p><h2 id=3D"advantages-of-naive-bayes-classifier" style=3D"t=
ext-align:left"><span>Advantages of Naive Bayes Classifier</span></h2><ul><=
li value=3D"1"><span>Easy to implement and computationally efficient.</span=
></li><li value=3D"2"><span>Effective in cases with a large number of featu=
res.</span></li><li value=3D"3"><span>Performs well even with limited train=
ing data.</span></li><li value=3D"4"><span>It performs well in the presence=
 of categorical features. </span></li><li value=3D"5"><span>For numerical f=
eatures data is assumed to come from normal distributions</span></li></ul><=
h2 id=3D"disadvantages-of-naive-bayes-classifier" style=3D"text-align:left"=
><span>Disadvantages of Naive Bayes Classifier</span></h2><ul><li value=3D"=
1"><span>Assumes that features are independent, which may not always hold i=
n real-world data.</span></li><li value=3D"2"><span>Can be influenced by ir=
relevant attributes.</span></li><li value=3D"3"><span>May assign zero proba=
bility to unseen events, leading to poor generalization.</span></li></ul><h=
2 id=3D"applications-of-naive-bayes-classifier" style=3D"text-align:left"><=
span>Applications of Naive Bayes Classifier</span></h2><ul><li value=3D"1">=
<b><strong>Spam Email Filtering</strong></b><span>: Classifies emails as sp=
am or non-spam based on features.</span></li><li value=3D"2"><b><strong>Tex=
t Classification</strong></b><span>: Used in sentiment analysis, document c=
ategorization and topic classification.</span></li><li value=3D"3"><b><stro=
ng>Medical Diagnosis:</strong></b><span> Helps in predicting the likelihood=
 of a disease based on symptoms.</span></li><li value=3D"4"><b><strong>Cred=
it Scoring:</strong></b><span> Evaluates creditworthiness of individuals fo=
r loan approval.</span></li><li value=3D"5"><b><strong>Weather Prediction</=
strong></b><span>: Classifies weather conditions based on various factors.<=
/span></li></ul>                               =20
